data.content:
Yes! Two better options depending on your needs:

**1. `[DataRow]` — simplest for constant values:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. Strongly-typed `DynamicData` — when you need runtime data:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key differences:**

- **`[DataRow]`** — inline, no separate property needed, but limited to compile-time constants (`string`, `bool`, `int`, etc.)
- **Typed `DynamicData`** — eliminates `object[]` boxing/casting, gives you named tuple fields, and supports runtime-computed values

Use `[DataRow]` here since your data is all constants. Switch to typed `DynamicData` when you need complex objects or computed values.

> **Note:** Strongly-typed `DynamicData` with tuples requires **MSTest v3.3+**.
